segments.text: And we're sitting out on the back porch of the new house, John and Maridel Coldis.
And I'm hoping that this machine is working as it should.
See, October 21st, visiting with John Coldis.
As a beginner, would you summarize, make believe that the person who might read or hear this would not know your background before you came to A&M University?
Give us a brief biographical summary of your experience before coming to A&M.
Okay.
Ready?
Yeah.
I'm originally from Gary, Indiana.
My dad came from Hungary.
My mom's parents came from Hungary.
They eventually came to Gary, Indiana because of the steel mills, and it provided an opportunity for Europeans who couldn't speak English to get a job and to make a living.
Grew up in Gary.
Went to the Gary, Indiana High School schools, specifically the Wallace High School.
Graduated in 1940.
I participated in athletics, football, basketball, and baseball.
I wanted to go to college, couldn't afford to do so.
Family couldn't afford to send me.
I went to work in the steel mills to make some money.
My high school coaches told me that they would help and look around and see if they could find an opportunity for me to walk on someplace and maybe earn a scholarship, an athletic scholarship.
Had the opportunity to go to Arkansas State University, did so.
Eventually, after a month or so, got a full scholarship in football.
Played football, baseball for four years, basketball one year.
Had a wonderful time at Arkansas State.
Majored in broad field science.
in education, and in history.
While I was in college, I participated in the ROTC program, and so upon graduation from college, I received a commission from the U.S. Army, Field Artillery, and in August of 1953,
My orders were to report for two years of military service.
Fortunately, the Korean War ended in July of 1953, and it was peacetime when I went in.
I really wanted to travel overseas.
As it turned out, I was stationed in Colorado Springs, Colorado, which is a beautiful place.
Enjoyed all of my time.
I was in the 4th Field Artillery Battalion, a 155 gun outfit.
It was an interesting period of time.
Got out of the service in 1955, started my teaching career in junior high at Blytheville, Arkansas.
Had an opportunity to go to the University of Toledo as a sports information person for my former football coach, Frost England.
I turned the job down because I wanted to do some coaching when I was younger.
The interesting thing was
that the salaries were not too dissimilar at a university and a junior high coaching job.
Coached for four years in Blytheville, Arkansas.
Enjoyed what I did.
Two years in junior high, two years in high school.
I left Blytheville in 1959 and joined the staff of Bum Phillips out at Amarillo High School, Amarillo Golden Sandstone, and was the assistant football coach, defensive backs,
and was the head baseball coach from 59 through 61.
When I got out of the service, I started my graduate work in the summer of 1956 at the University of Arkansas.
Under the old GI Bill, you had seven years to use up everything you had coming.
And so I had planned to go back full-time in 61 to use all that up and get my doctoral degree by 63.
What I decided early on as a child that I wanted to teach, as I left the college campus, I thought that I really wanted to get back and teach on the college campus.
So my orientation was in that direction.
Took my first college job, East Texas State University, on the faculty there in 1963, June 1 of 1963.
Enjoyed my time.
I was in the health and physical education department at that time.
And Justin Hawthorne, head of the department, super guy, took a very good period.
At the time, Doe Rollins, who had been dean of men at Texas A&M, was the dean of men at East Texas State.
And the football coach was a man by the name of Coach Sykes, who had coached Texas A&M.
Those two used to tell me a lot of stories about Texas A&M and came back to make more sense years later when I came to A&M.
Taught for four years.
We had a new president that came in during that fourth year and he began to reorganize the administrative staff of the institution.
And he was looking for a person who had an excellent student orientation to serve as the dean of students at that time.
And he had gotten good word about me from a number of people.
So he called me in one day, unbeknownst to me that he was thinking about it.
And I was the chairman of the faculty committee on traffic safety and security.
And I assumed that's what we were going to talk about.
And he offered me the job as dean of students.
Now, that's when?
And so Meridel and I talked it over.
The thing that we talked about was that I was happy doing what I was doing.
I always wanted to be in the classroom.
And I had never thought about the administration, career administration, straight line administration.
So we talked, and we decided to give it a couple of years, and decided we would enjoy it, and we'd stay.
And if we didn't, we'd go back to full-time teaching.
As a part of that agreement, the president at that time was Whit Halliday.
Part of that agreement was that I'd be allowed to continue in the classroom.
So he was agreeable to that without any problem.
And so I continued to teach all that period of time.
So I served as VP.
Well, they changed the title the next year from Dean of Students to Vice President.
I served with under Dr. Whit Halliday for five of those years.
Worked with Bob McDowell, who was vice president for finance.
At the end of the fifth year, during that year, Whit's wife committed suicide.
And so he decided to move.
And Bob became president.
And so I served one year with Bob as vice president.
Hated to leave Bob.
because he was a good man and wanted to help him with his presidency.
The opportunities at Texas A&M, I thought, were too great to pass up.
How did you and A&M come together?
Who contacted whom?
We have an organization of student personnel administrators in the state called CUSPA.
And Dean Hannigan and Howard Perry were members of that group.
And in fact, we had worked closely together.
I was the executive secretary of that association.
And the Southwest Association as well, which took in four Southwest states.
And they told me that Dean Hannigan was getting ready to retire.
and they wondered if I might not be interested in a job.
I said, you know, yeah.
Of all these schools in the state of Texas that would fit my orientation, I think A&M would be as close as any.
And so they just chatted with me about that.
And the next contact was by Dr. Williams.
He called me one afternoon and on the telephone asked me if I might be interested in it.
And if so, if I would come and visit him.
I'd never met, to my knowledge, Jack Williams before that.
I had never visited with him in any way about anything.
So that was the contact.
And that was when?
That was in the spring of...
So he had been here then a year?
So he'd been here two years plus because he came in the fall of November 1 of 70.
What was your impression of him on first contact, first impressions?
My first visit down was an interesting one.
His office, of course, was in the building named after him, the administration building.
And Elder Rowell met me and Dr. Williams had an appointment at the time and he was running just a little bit late.
So Nelda introduced me to two young students who were finishing up their degrees and they had me join them for a cup of coffee.
One was Kent Caperton and the other was Roger Miller.
And so I had coffee with those two kids and they were super and we had a good chat.
All of a sudden Nelda said Dr. Williams was ready and available

We went in and we didn't talk but a couple minutes and he shoveled me off to Howard Perry and I was on my way for the day and so I had lunch with the faculty and staff and students and did a bunch of things around the campus and my day was over and Howard Perry asked me if there was anything else that I would like to do and I said well
Well, I had a talk with Dr. Williams.
I guess he was busy and you know, I'd like to talk, chat with him about some concerns that I had.
And so Howard called over to Nelda and Nelda said, oh yeah, his schedule is wide open.
So my thought was, he wasn't interested in me.
And so when I went by the office, I chatted with him a little bit about those concerns, and I drove back to Commerce that late afternoon, early evening.
And my thought was he was not interested, and so he just had me down to visit, and that was it.
Found out later that he had made up his mind very quickly that I was the one that he wanted for the job.
And he didn't need to talk to me anymore.
But he was such a bright man.
I enjoyed the conversations with him.
He had a good sense of humor, most people didn't know that.
When I first came back,
He called me and had me come by and he wanted to give me his assessment of all the key administrative people on campus at that time.
And basically who he trusted and who he didn't and who he liked and who he didn't like.
And so that was, you know, that was great for me to find out immediately about all the people on campus.
It was an interesting discussion and conversation that I will never forget.
All right, now this first
this first visit, was that your only pre-offer visit?
What were your concerns as you came for that visit?
What were you wanting to learn?
Well, I had been to A&M a couple times in the past on recruiting visits, recruiting staff.
And so I was familiar with the campus.
I had talked to enough people over the years and, of course, the fact that I went to the University of Arkansas and A&M was a part of the Southwest Conference, you know, I knew quite a bit about A&M.
Plus, in the service, summer camp, so my contact and association with A&M had more depth to it than, you know, just the first visit and coming on campus to meet with Dr. Williams.
I felt real good about A&M.
I felt real good about the opportunities here.
And when I say opportunities, I think anybody that goes into some kind of profession wants to be able to do a lot of good things professionally.
And for the most part, just about anything that you go into, it takes money.
and East Texas State did not have the financial resources.
And when I said opportunities, one, they really didn't have a good student-like program at A&M at the time.
So the sky was the limit there.
Plus, in regard to the money, I thought a lot of money could be brought into the program to develop a real first-class program.
Although I came afield,
when I came into the student personnel business.
I learned very quickly what in the world the profession was and what it took and what it was all about.
And I really worked hard at learning.
And in regard to a good student life program, you need staff and you need money and you need facilities.
Did Dr. Williams have any specific goals that he gave you?
The most important one to him at that time

He had seen Dean Hannigan as a good man, but a military man, and that in regard to our student body, the voluntary Corps of Cadet program, and the size of the student body as it increased, using our terminology here, was going to be mostly civilian and very small numbers in the Corps of Cadets.
And so he was concerned that
We'd take care of all the students.
Secondly, and I say secondly, equal to that was concern about women and involving the women.
And then, of course, we just, all the institutions in the state of Texas had not been integrated that far.
And so he had a concern also about the integration of the minorities into A&M and into the student line program.
So those were his major.
He was super as an administrator in the sense that when he brought you in to do a job, he didn't tell you all the things he wanted you to do.
He mentioned what his concerns was.
But it was yours to run with.
And so the period of time that I worked with him.
He would not agree to everything just because you thought it was a good idea.
And on numerous occasions when I had meetings with him, especially about major problems, we'd reach an impasse.
And he was very strong.
He'd get very strong.
And on those occasions, I would just kind of back off.
And I'd wait until he was emotionally back down to a good level, emotionally more stable, before I'd approach that subject or whatever again.
In every case, he was always agreeable to doing what I thought would be best for the program.
So as an administrator that worked for him, he was the best that you could have.
Let's make believe someone had never seen Dr. Williams.
Describe him physically.
He was about average height.
I call it a square face.
His body build was almost that same way.
Always a smile.
Unless he was emotionally involved or serious about something, he was relaxed and very personable, casual.
I say square because he was, through the thoracic region, was a broad-chested individual.
He was a well-built man.
I never saw him in shorts.
We played golf together a lot, but he never wore shorts on a golf course.
But well-built individual.
What were his relaxing activities?
What did he do?
One, he loved to play golf.
Most people didn't know that.
It's interesting that you would say relaxing.
I'm not sure it was that relaxing, but it took his mind off of what he did day by day.
Did you all play at the university courts?
No, oh no.
We played down in Brocker.
He didn't want to play with him.
There were only
two other people that he played with, of which I'm aware.
One was General Simpson, and that was only at the beginning when General Simpson went to work for me.
That kind of dropped off by the wayside.
And the other one was Bob Rucker, who ended up at Grounds.
You know, Bob was the what?
Yeah, Grounds Mains person.
Yeah, headed that up.
Bob had an artificial left hand, but, you know, played well.
I played well for that handicap that he had.
Dr. Williams was a well-coordinated individual, but he had started playing golf late in life.
And the funniest thing that if there was a tree within
hundred yards and it could be only two inches in diameter, he'd find that tree.
And I never did hear him curse, but I heard words and sounds.
But he would slip out to the golf course and slip on back in.
He really didn't want to be seen by anybody.
He really didn't want to interact with anybody other than with the group he was playing.
And did he have other activities that were getaway, relax?
You know, other than family and home, I can't think of anything else.
Because I don't know about fishing or hunting or long vacations.
He really lived his job 24 hours a day.
Did you become aware during your years working with him that his Clemson experience was of value here at A&M?
Do you remember any examples of that?
Well, he had these good friends from Clemson that came to visit.
that came as a staff member, I'm trying to think of his, Hugh McCauley, Hugh and Pinky McCauley.
We had, Meridel and I saw Hugh and Pinky on a trip to Alaska, and Hugh was losing his eyesight, and cannot see anymore, he's blind.
But in regard to,
Clemson, I think, is a great deal like A&M.
And I think it's a very conservative institution, conservative student body, conservative faculty and staff for the most part.
So I think that all fit in to who Jack Williams was and was all about.
And when I say conservative, I think probably
When you say those terms, General Rutter was conservative, but there are two different types of conservative persons.
Jack Williams was conservative as it related to finances and money.
He wanted to save a penny.
He wanted to use whatever money he had to develop
good programs and programs that we needed within him academically.
He wanted to have an outstanding faculty.
He wanted to have an outstanding student body.
That meant increasing salaries, more scholarships, and all of that.
So he wasn't conservative in the same way that General Rudder was conservative, but philosophically conservative.
He had a lot of things that he wanted to do that were not supported by the Board of Regents.
And he tried to gain the confidence and the relationship with the Board of Regents so he could implement more of those things that he wanted to.
For example, I know he wanted the fraternities and sororities.
He thought they would be good for our campus because they would involve more of the male and females
student activities of one type or another that were not in the core of cadets and the board was not interested back at that time.
Did you and or he bring that issue up in any way with board members?
He told me at the time that he would keep it in his back pocket and hit the board when it was the right time.
It never became full-blown early on
And the fraternities and sororities that were initiated were initiated off campus without the relationship with Texas A&M.
Did you and Dr. Williams ever discuss fraternities and sororities?
Oh, many, many times.
I was very supportive.
I'm trying to think of the name of the committee.
Was it Target 2000?
I think probably.
I think that probably was it.
We had a committee.
We had a whole bunch of committees.
and one related to student life.
And I know on that committee we had a number of old legs, one of them being a Searcy Brace one.
And I remember I used to approach that group all the time.
That was back in the early 70s about how important it was for us to have attorneys and sororities recognized on our particular campus.
The one I told them, and Dr. Williams agreed,
that if they were going to be here, it would be better for us to have a relationship with them than not have any relationship at all.
And I thought any student organization could have a positive impact, both upon the students and the campus, if you take that orientation.
And so those people, sort of seeing a number of other people,
The fact that they like Dr. Williams and they like me, they listen to us in terms of...
There were a couple board members, Julie Bell being one, and I'm not sure who else was around.
They were totally against it and opposed to it.
And then what happened was that got all locked up in the Melanie Zentgraf case.

When the federal judge in Houston ruled that the gay student services organization was a social organization, and since A&M did not recognize fraternities and sororities, they didn't have to recognize the gay student services organization.
So it got tied up in that, and so therefore the board was not about to recognize it then.
And then when it went to the Fifth Circuit Court of Appeals,
and they reversed that decision, then fraternities and sororities, as well as the gay student services organizations, were able to be recognized.
Let's hold that whole thing for a while.
commencement to attend as an A&M employee, I was seated this close to her when she did not get her hand shaken.
With Bill Hobby right here, we were shooting the breeze.
All right, let's go back to your early days.
Who were the key people in the student affairs area when you came?
The
Tom Parsons was the Commandant of the Corps of Cadets.
And back at that time, the person that served as head of the Army ROTC program by virtue of that position, a military officer, was the Commandant.
Charles Powell was the Dean of Men.
Toby Reeves was the Dean of Women.
Hal Poe was the Director of Student Health Services.
J. Wayne Stark was the
and director of Memorial Student Center.
Bob Logan was the director of financial aid, although Bob Logan did not work for me then, financial aid reported the academic center.
So those were there.
And they had all, pretty well all of those were veterans, weren't they?
Except for maybe Toby.
They'd been here a good while.
And y'all were, by and large, y'all were quartered where?
mostly in the YMCA building.
And, of course, the Student Center people, you know, were over in the Student Center.
Back at that time, Wayne Stark had student government and all the student organizations and the Student Center Council, so he was really
key person for all student organizations and I thought that was too much and that we ought to separate it out.
The programming part of the MSC, I had done the same thing at East Texas State when I took over there.
After I got involved with it, I thought it was, it would
Two separate programs in a whole lot of different issues.
I saw the student center as a programming operation for the entire campus.
Provide all kinds of programs.
I saw student government and student organizations as being separate and apart from that.
Student government, of course, for the student body to represent itself to me, the president of the institution, and to the faculty.
and student activities, I thought there ought to be a zillion organizations.
One of the things that I liked about the Corps is the fact that you operate in small groups and you have this affiliation with a few people.
And if that's a good situation, then you feel good about the larger unit.
and eventually to the university.
And so as long as it was legal and didn't cost us too much money, we could support any new student organization.
So Carolyn Adair hired Carolyn in the summer of 74 to be director of student activities.
Now, she had been working?
On the MSC staff.
So she was familiar with that part of it.
but worked for J. Wayne Stark.
Generalize about Wayne Stark.
Describe him and his efforts and so forth.
Wayne had a tremendous interest in young people, in working with young people, in seeing young people succeed and better themselves.
do great things.
He was an interesting guy in the sense that he would fight whomever, General Rutter and whoever else, if he thought he was right and they were wrong in regard to what he needed to do.
We had a super relationship because I respected who he was and what he did.
I had to be careful though because Dr. Williams was not General Rudder.
